{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535295"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:54:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:54:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.01,0.71,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61049"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8012"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"403"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19473"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61049"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of right flank pain, fever, and rigours. She reports dysuria and frequency. She has a medical history of poorly controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus with a recent HbA1c of 98 mmol/mol. Her only medication is metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. There is marked right costovertebral angle tenderness. Abdominal examination reveals right flank tenderness but is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 18.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 245 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose: 18.2 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan with contrast shows a 4 cm fluid collection in the upper pole of the right kidney with peripheral enhancement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Emphysematous pyelonephritis","Renal cell carcinoma","Renal abscess","Perinephric haematoma","Simple renal cyst"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of fever, flank pain, and urinary symptoms, along with raised inflammatory markers and CT findings of a rim-enhancing fluid collection, is highly characteristic. The patient\u0027s poorly controlled diabetes is a significant risk factor, as it impairs immune function and increases susceptibility to complicated urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmphysematous pyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe, necrotising infection of the kidney that typically occurs in diabetic patients. However, CT would show gas in the renal parenchyma rather than a focal fluid collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with solid rather than cystic masses on imaging. While it can present with fever and constitutional symptoms, the acute presentation with urinary symptoms and marked inflammatory response makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerinephric haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would typically occur after trauma or in patients on anticoagulation, neither of which is present here. The CT appearance would show acute blood rather than a rim-enhancing collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple renal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a thin-walled, non-enhancing lesion on CT and would not cause systemic symptoms or inflammatory response. The peripheral enhancement seen on CT is characteristic of an abscess rather than a simple cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of renal abscess is important to recognise as it requires specific management with both antibiotics and drainage for optimal outcomes. Common causative organisms include \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renal abscesses commonly present with fever, flank pain, and features of urinary tract infection.","Diabetes mellitus is a significant risk factor for renal and perinephric abscesses.","CT with contrast is the imaging modality of choice for diagnosing renal abscesses."],"references":["Zulfiqar M, Ubilla CV, Nicola R, Menias CO. Imaging of Renal Infections and Inflammatory Disease. Radiol Clin North Am. 2020;58(5):909-923. doi:10.1016/j.rcl.2020.05.004"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-14T20:48:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-14T20:49:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8012"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61049"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun